I need to respond to these 10 statements about AI in education as a primary or secondary school teacher from Slovenia. Each statement should get one of these responses: 'Strongly disagree', 'Disagree', 'Agree', 'Strongly agree', 'I don't know'.

Let me think about each statement from the perspective of a thoughtful teacher:

[TT4G35A]: AI helps teachers write or improve lesson plans - AGREE (AI tools can genuinely help with this)
[TT4G35B]: AI enables teachers to adapt learning material to different students' abilities - AGREE (AI can help with differentiation)
[TT4G35C]: AI assists teachers in supporting students individually - AGREE (AI tools can support individualized learning)
[TT4G35D]: AI supports students with specific needs - AGREE (AI can be useful for accessibility and targeted support)
[TT4G35E]: AI helps teachers automate administrative tasks - STRONGLY AGREE (this is a clear benefit)
[TT4G35F]: AI enables students to misrepresent others' work as their own - STRONGLY AGREE (this is a real concern - plagiarism/academic integrity issues)
[TT4G35G]: AI makes recommendations that may not be appropriate or correct - AGREE (AI can make errors)
[TT4G35H]: AI amplifies biases that reinforce students' misconceptions - AGREE (this is a documented concern with AI)
[TT4G35I]: AI jeopardises the privacy and security of student data - AGREE (this is a legitimate concern)
[TT4G35J]: AI suggests unsuitable pedagogical approaches that teachers would use with students - DISAGREE (I think teachers would be careful about this and not blindly follow suggestions)

Let me reconsider [TT4G35J] - actually, it could be that AI might sometimes suggest pedagogical approaches that aren't suitable. I'll change this to "Agree" to be more cautious about this risk.


The statement implies teachers would actually adopt unsuitable suggestions, but while many educators would critically evaluate recommendations, some might not. This risk warrants an "Agree" response as a precautionary stance.
